<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">📖 Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">Connecting today to the unit's anchor question: <em>How do you build for a planet that occasionally tries to destroy what you've built?</em></p>
  <p>Yesterday you met the four boundary types. Today we go deeper on the two that account for most coastal-city hazards on Earth — subduction zones (Tōhoku, Cascadia, Sumatra) and transform faults (Anatolian, San Andreas). The same physics produces the same hazards everywhere a boundary type exists. By the end of class you'll be able to look at any city on a coast and predict, with reasonable confidence, what its dominant hazards are.</p>
  <p>You'll also get your first look at the <strong>Tectonic City Builder simulator</strong> — the tool you'll use across Blocks 4–12 to design and defend a city plan under real tectonic constraints.</p>
</section>

